While gift cards proved sufficient initially, announcing the addition of bicycles in December and perhaps a hybrid or electric car in January might have sustained or even increased engagement rather than allowing it to decline.

While examining the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I decided to view all fifteen trick films produced between 1895 and 1901. These films typically employ creative editing techniques to create illusions. My film analysis primarily focused on describing the poetics of most trick films and investigating the evolutionary outlier characteristics found in some of the later works. At the turn of the century, trick films were largely bound to sets, composed within a frontal proscenium arch, featured no camera movement, utilized long and medium shots, and strictly followed the principle of one shot equals one film. However, some films emerging at the start of the twentieth century dared to challenge these conventions by introducing elements such as multiple shots.

A key common feature of these trick films is their filming on interior sets within a frontal proscenium frame. The camera remains stationary in its proscenium position, never following figures or objects. This composition style, deeply rooted in theater and particularly in vaudeville and magic performances, was prevalent in early cinema. One limitation of this stage-based approach is that characters in trick films typically move only laterally, rarely approaching or retreating from the camera. This is exemplified in "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900), where actors enter from the right and move along a horizontal axis, with the camera remaining fixed even when they exit the frame.

The frontal proscenium composition naturally led to the predominance of long shots and occasional medium shots. Close-ups are notably absent from all trick films in the Edison catalog. This approach mirrors theatrical and vaudeville traditions, where audiences viewed the entire performance within the stage's boundaries at all times. As typical of early films, actors rarely moved from the middle ground toward the camera, precluding the occurrence of close-ups.

Most early trick films adhered to the principle that one conceptual shot constituted an entire film. This restricted most trick films to approximately one minute or less, depending on the frame rate, and limited their dramatic or narrative scope. Most focused on brief vaudeville-style illusions, such as magic tricks, disappearances, and transformations, with minimal storytelling. However, it's worth noting that in trick films, what appears as one conceptual shot to viewers often comprises multiple physical shots combined to create illusion effects. This is evident in "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" (1895), where careful observation reveals the splice point where the shot with Mary's "severed head" begins, despite the film appearing as one continuous shot to viewers.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" represents, both in essence and name, an "oxymoron of 'Old-New'" as Ian Watt explains in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic mode has experienced both criticism and praise, facing accusations of superficiality while simultaneously being celebrated for its ability to evoke the 'terrible sublime' (Burke). The original Gothic novel, Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, merged elements from both "ancient and modern" romances to establish the proto-Gothic genre and pioneer a new form of literary expression. Walpole combines "old" theatrical elements with 'new' natural mimicry found in 'modern' novels to present what he calls "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre heavily draws from medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and customs. Even when The Castle of Otranto was published, the term "gothic" had already been applied to various peoples, styles, and historical periods. It was often viewed as outdated or unsophisticated compared to "modern" social and literary "progress." The fusion of theatrical "Gothic" elements with the novel's new format (which offers readers intimate access to character psychology) has enabled Gothic literature to endure while simultaneously appearing both antiquated and fresh to readers far removed from its original context.

One of the most significant gothic concepts present in Gothic novels is Chivalry. The medieval notion of chivalry, encompassing the training of proper knights, is both preserved and transformed in The Castle of Otranto. Gothic writers, particularly Walpole, emphasized chivalry because it represented an ideal - the classic knight, embodying bravery, honor, and competence - which they perceived as lacking in their contemporary society. Through the incorporation of chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" becomes idealized and romanticized (foreshadowing Gothic literature's evolution into Romanticism) and serves as a tool for contemporary social critique. When Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto, he was experiencing political turbulence and harbored concerns about the future. Immersed in politics and facing (arguably) unfair accusations, he may have concluded, perhaps unconsciously, that the moral integrity and inherent "goodness" associated with the gothic era had somehow diminished in contemporary society. This concept is clearly illustrated through several characters, particularly Frederic, who embodies numerous chivalric traits and is portrayed through traditionally chivalric imagery: as a prince who has endured suffering, been appropriately affected by tragedy, and is believed to have fallen to infidels. The figure of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is deliberately exaggerated, introducing the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management is the flow of processes that move goods from customer orders through raw materials, supply, production, and product distribution to the customer. The term supply chain management was coined in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver. Keith Oliver described the comprehensive process of planning, implementing, and controlling the supply chain to meet customer needs quickly and efficiently. A supply chain consists of six key elements: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers utilize these six key elements to deliver optimal customer service.

Production serves as the foundation and first step in the supply chain process. It defines the when, why, where, and how of all production activities. Managers must understand customer demands, primarily by analyzing market trends, which serve as the strongest indicator of customer needs. Once managers have assessed market demands, they can determine which products to manufacture and in what quantities. They then select optimal production facilities based on volume capabilities and quality standards, while ensuring customer satisfaction remains paramount. The next phase involves scheduling workloads and equipment maintenance. Production is crucial to the supply chain process, with every detail being vital. Improper planning can result in significant time and financial losses. For instance, from my experience at Walmart and Target, these retailers maintain detailed protocols for everything from employee uniforms to receiving shipments, ensuring smooth operations through clear directives and expectations.

The second key element, supply, involves making strategic decisions about a facility's core capabilities and determining appropriate outsourcing partnerships. A single product may involve multiple production divisions, each with distinct equipment, workforce, and expertise. Managers must determine which division best suits each production process, sometimes opting to outsource work to external companies. The primary motivation for outsourcing is to achieve velocity - the ability to maintain quality and flexibility while reducing or maintaining low costs.

Victorian novels are distinguished by their overwhelming attention to detail and their focus on the period's aristocracy. Two novels that are considered Victorian but deviate from this tradition are "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights". Both novels employ elements of mystery and an inclination toward the bizarre, uncommon for novels of this period, which strengthens the characters in each work and provides insights into their motivations and emotions.

"And now crowds of bewildering and confusing thoughts pressed upon his mind. He seemed to still be walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were arguing furiously: for the words they spoke rang in his ears; and when he caught his own attention... he discovered he was talking to them.... Suddenly he recoiled at the sound of firearms; loud screams and shouts rose up; lights flashed before his eyes, and everything was noise and chaos, as an invisible hand hurriedly pulled him away. Through all these rapid visions ran an undefined, uncomfortable sensation of pain that tormented him ceaselessly."

The two novels frequently utilize this mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, though the content and function varies in each specific instance. In Oliver Twist, these strange occurrences often reveal insights into Oliver's inner world, his pain, and his awareness of the true nature of events unfolding around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, Oliver vividly relives the shooting, as if in a dream, while struggling to find help. The passage emphasizes Oliver's lack of control over the unfolding events, as well as his dire health condition, strongly evident through his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit.

A few years ago, I worked as a tutor in an after-school program for elementary school students. I did my best to help them in all subjects they struggled with, though my strengths were in English and reading. One of the teachers recruited me to help a young boy named Adrian (I believe he was in third or fourth grade) who was having significant difficulties with reading. I realized something wasn't quite right; he was experiencing the most unusual problems. Some letters he could pronounce perfectly, others not at all - it was quite puzzling. While he was clearly of Latino heritage, his spoken English was flawless.

Things continued this way until I met his mother. I was supervising a few remaining students while the rest of the after-school group was on a field trip when she came in. His mother didn't speak any English, only Spanish. Despite my limited Spanish skills (I was just learning), we managed to communicate. That's when it hit me like lightning: Adrian could read well enough, he just wasn't fully familiar with the English alphabet.

I share this story to highlight the language barrier challenges in schools, particularly in California, and to show that these issues aren't always obvious. Even for children who speak perfect English, reading can present significant obstacles. While we all acknowledge this problem exists, what's the solution? In Adrian's case, it was relatively straightforward: tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for many children who barely speak English, the solution is far more complex. No single approach - whether dual language programs, mainstream immersion, private tutoring, or ESL classes - can solve this alone. The key lies in combining all these methods.

The dual language system, in particular, is an excellent approach - not just for native Spanish speakers, but for all children. Research shows that students in two-way bilingual education programs often outperform their peers academically. While some fear this approach wastes resources or won't benefit the majority of students, this is incorrect. If we implemented these programs as standard practice rather than exception, all children would benefit. Does this mean requiring all teachers to be bilingual? No, that would be unreasonable and impractical. However, there's no reason we can't have bilingual teaching assistants and tutors to support this approach.

From childhood on, most of us are taught that there is something greater than ourselves, greater than we can comprehend. Some of us are sent to Sunday school to learn about it, while others go to temple or search within themselves for answers. Many of us readily accept the religions passed down to us by our parents. Some, however, reject them completely, denying that anything beyond knowing could exist in our own egocentric universe. We might adopt one value system, only to later change our minds and replace it with another. Whatever path we choose, we journey to define a part of ourselves through our own unique perspectives on spirituality. We search for a light in the darkness to guide us from the shadows into the sunlight.

"A cardinal," my father replied when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on the front porch of our house, listening to the rain drumming on the tin roof above while smoking our cigarettes together. The gutters channeled the rain down, flooding the plants along the porch's edge. He gazed into the rain with a look that seemed half-searching, half-remembering. He had grown thinner in recent months, his clothes hanging loosely on his frame. His hair had thinned too, sparser than I remembered. He continued staring into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt isolated, frightened, and unable to tell my father how much I would miss him, because speaking of it would only make it more real for both of us. I embraced him, returned to my seat, moved my chair closer to his, and joined him in watching the falling rain in the June twilight.

My father died that December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemotherapy and radiation hadn't eased his suffering, but had kept him alive several months beyond the doctors' predictions; I couldn't determine the value in merely prolonging his suffering. What kind of God would do this, I wondered. Alone in the night, I offered no prayers. If God existed, I thought, He had long since stopped listening to me.

I hadn't wanted to witness his passage from this life into another. So I didn't. I couldn't watch the life that created me as it ended. I wanted to remember my father by how he lived rather than how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than they did, better than his family did, and knew Dad wouldn't want his only child to be a spectator to his death. I curled up in my bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate of Republicanism. Although he was primarily a farmer, this profession combined with his brief political career made him a man known for his commitment and candor in matters of personal liberty and governance. His devotion to an agricultural system formed the foundation for virtually all his views on government. His effort to preserve and promote what he considered the most noble of all professions shaped his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

He believed that the United States had a unique opportunity to create an ideal system, as there were no established traditions to constrain the nation's founders, enabling the creation of true self-governance. He was a strong believer in humanity's natural rights, maintaining that these rights were interconnected—if one was compromised, all would eventually fail, diminishing the value of those remaining. These rights, he argued, must remain beyond government's reach.

Taylor believed that an effective government must account for humanity's inherent capacity for both good and evil. He was uncompromising in his views on moral dualism, asserting that since government is administered by humans, it must reflect both human virtues and vices. He identified positive principles as those protecting private property, advancing agriculture, and limiting capitalism, believing that a government founded on sound principles would function justly regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be driven by self-interest and greed.

As a dedicated Republican of his era, Taylor advocated for strict constitutional interpretation. He favored a severely limited federal government, restricted to only those powers explicitly granted by the Constitution. He understood that an expansive federal government would be costly and likely tyrannical. However, he cautioned against overly literal interpretation, arguing that without understanding the founders' intent, such an approach could become corrupted. Notably, he regarded the Declaration of Independence as the nation's true charter, as it more clearly defined the country as a union of sovereign states rather than a single unified nation.

Downward I gazed, my mind blankly processing the scene before me. With detached observation and practiced awareness, I studied the sight before my eyes, refusing to connect it to any deeper meaning. Thoughts drifted in and out of my consciousness almost faster than they could form. My mind worked with such fluid efficiency that it seemed I wasn't truly thinking at all, but rather experiencing a pure, liquid awareness of what lay before me.

Once, following an artist's recommendation, I bought an instructional book titled "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." Since age six, I had yearned to learn drawing, and this book covered everything from basic pencil handling to how the brain processes linear information. One technique involved placing a square frame around the subject being studied, transforming an overwhelmingly complex scene - like a fruit bowl in a kitchen connected to a dining room - into a manageable composition of a simple bowl on a plane.

In that moment, staring down at the bowl before me, I couldn't mentally construct that artist's frame. I was too overwhelmed, too astounded to do anything but stand there in amazement. While Picasso had his Blue Period, Monet his fascination with greenery, and Renaissance masters their spectrum of colors, here before me - if I dared consider my perspective artistic - lay the beginning of my own masterpiece: "Work in Brown."

My fingertips grasped my chosen artistic tool, muscles tensing and relaxing as my hand moved through space, my mind's intention taking physical form in what might have been my most creative moment. Water swirled, peaceful and smooth, pristine and clear. Particles broke free and disappeared into nothingness. With increasing urgency, my hand struck the toilet handle again. The stubborn brown mass refused to budge, adhering like a slug to the bowl's bottom.

Standing there in my green tie that chafed at my neck, feet planted shoulder-width apart and mop loosely held, I frowned slightly at the crude deposit of processed organic matter someone had left as a greeting for the unfortunate souls who cleaned the Rite Aid bathrooms. After several more flushes and moments of quiet contemplation, my hand reached for the toilet paper, wrapping itself until it resembled a makeshift glove. Standing straight, then bending at the waist, my hand descended slowly into the bowl, like a mother reaching into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

Teenagers are losing their lives while driving. Multiple factors contribute to this deadly statistical trend among America's youngest drivers. The National Institutes of Health explain that one aspect of the problem is that the adolescent brain is literally not prepared for the dangers of driving. Lack of experience is also at the core of the problem. This inexperience not only leads to more fatal accidents but also results in higher rates of vehicle rollovers, speeding, and running off the road.

Young people are particularly at risk when traveling with peers - which anyone with common sense knows happens regularly. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study demonstrating a correlation between passenger age and the number of traffic accidents.

California and other states have attempted to enhance teen driver safety through provisional licenses that restrict driving hours and prohibit other minors as passengers.

However, provisional licenses are, in my opinion, merely temporary solutions. The real issue is that young drivers, as a group, are simply not capable of adequately handling the risks and responsibilities, according to all statistical indicators. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes that even 18 is too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman's research indicates a common desire among those under 19-20 years old to take risks purely for the thrill of it.

This paper examines three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). Initially, it provides a concise definition of the disorder. Subsequently, it explains the diagnostic process, including common characteristics or "warning signs." The paper concludes by discussing methods through which teachers in mainstream classroom settings can support students with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), refers to how effectively the central nervous system (CNS) processes auditory information. In its narrow definition, (C)AP describes the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the underlying neurobiological activity that generates electrophysiological auditory potentials (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). In essence, it is a condition where the central nervous system (the brain) cannot properly process auditory inputs. Individuals with CAPD have normal hearing capabilities and are not considered hearing impaired; rather, the brain regions responsible for translating auditory input, distinguishing words, or separating conversation from background noise do not function typically.

The disorder that eventually became known as CAPD was first documented in the mid-1950s under the term "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) during studies of children with communication disorders. In 1954, the Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing diagnostic tests. In 1961, Kimura introduced dichotic testing and proposed a model explaining the CANS physiology underlying dichotic perception. A significant national conference in 1977 sparked increased research into children with CAPD.

CAPD presents in various ways: affected individuals may struggle with sound localization; have difficulty distinguishing between multiple acoustic events; be unable to recognize sound patterns; struggle to detect vocal nuances (such as identifying sarcasm through voice changes); experience auditory masking where one sound blocks another; have difficulty synthesizing sound cues into meaningful, actionable information; and struggle with sequencing auditory information (Ferre).

CAPD diagnosis requires systematic evaluation of listening behavior and/or performance on auditory function tests, conducted by professionals including audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using various assessment tools. The diagnostic process may include questionnaires, behavioral observations, and evaluation of responses to specific stimuli. Currently, there is no single, universally accepted diagnostic tool with high success rates, and the disorder's cause remains unknown. Many diagnostic procedures involve presenting multiple simultaneous auditory stimuli and asking patients to differentiate specific elements, such as word or number sequences. More sophisticated tests include measuring acoustic signals within the ear and analyzing response patterns.

In pursuing my social work education, I aim to build a career with the Department of Family and Children's Services to support abused or neglected children and assist families in crisis. The values I bring to social work include: service, respect, ethical conduct, dedication to improving relationships between others, and commitment to my own professional development to maintain competency in my field. These core values aren't just important for social workers; they hold deep personal significance for me.

I've always felt drawn to helping others, though I was initially uncertain about my career path. During my high school and college years, I witnessed many people avoiding their problems, some using less-than-ideal coping mechanisms. These experiences led me to pursue a Psychology degree. After graduating from Piedmont College in 2009, I took some time off. That summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a nervous sixteen-year-old boy on her couch. She explained he was fleeing from abusive parents. The next day, I learned he had called the police to his parents' home. Wanting to help, I drove there, shared my concerns with the police, and mentioned my Psychology degree. The police asked me to speak with the parents since they had no legal recourse. The parents appeared nervous and justified their son's "manipulative" behavior in what they called "simple" disputes. This experience sparked my serious consideration of a social work career.

Social justice is another crucial value in social work. As a society, we claim to value individuality and mourn those we've lost, yet our concept of "individuality" often follows outdated traditions rather than embracing true uniqueness. If we mourn lost individuals, why do we strive to conform? I am an individual who resists self-imposed limitations. Throughout my academic years, I protested social injustice through various means: dyeing my hair unconventional colors, wearing clothes that expressed my personality, getting multiple ear piercings, actively participating in GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and confronting racism and discrimination whenever I encountered it. I believe in social justice and will continue to stand against social injustice.

The following paper examines the biological and sociocultural models in relation to the sleep disorder insomnia. The biological model concentrates on inherited genetic information as well as medical aspects of health. The sociocultural models examine environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia examines these models and explains each piece of selected research to relate to and better explain the models. The research explanations and their findings are then evaluated to highlight their specific strengths and limitations.

I have been studying at University Park for about two and a half years now, equivalent to four and a half semesters. For many students, including myself, getting around campus can be challenging. During my freshman year, I was assigned to a dorm room in East Halls - practically at the easternmost edge of campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. The journey from my residence in Stuart Hall to classes in distant locations like the Willard building, near campus center, could take up to 25 minutes on foot, especially in State College's frequently adverse weather conditions.

In conversation with a recent alumnus, I discovered that not long ago, East Halls was separated from the main campus by vast stretches of unused land. Today, that space has been transformed with sports fields, impressive new structures including the new Creamery and health services building, and is now surrounded by apartment complexes. As our campus continues to grow, transportation between locations becomes increasingly challenging. What's the ideal solution to this mobility issue? On a college campus, it's the bicycle. However, bikes alone aren't the answer - students need to use them, and the campus infrastructure must accommodate cyclists' needs.

Recently, I spoke with a friend who had returned to cycling after several years away from it. He wondered why he'd ever stopped, saying, "Bikes are fantastic - there was a period when cycling wasn't considered cool, but it's really the most practical way to get around." Beyond its health benefits, cycling is the most efficient mode of transportation. A simple breakfast and some physical effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many upperclassmen, I now reside off-campus, just as far from the center as some dorms. Purchasing a bike was my wisest decision this year. I have daily classes in Thomas building, normally a 25-minute walk from my residence. By bicycle, I can make this journey in just 5 minutes when riding at a good pace. The only challenge is that Pollock Road, while the most direct route to Thomas building from my home, isn't always easy to navigate, whether on bike or foot. While walking has its merits, my schedule is too tight for it. Without my bike, walking would be my only dependable option for reaching classes. Walking to Thomas daily would consume an extra 30-40 minutes of my time - that's over two and a half hours weekly. Factor in all the additional time spent walking to other classes and appointments, and it becomes an unsustainable time commitment.

Aldous Huxley critiques the looming dangers of technology and capitalistic structures through his dystopian vision in Brave New World. In his created society, communal values supersede individual identity, with citizens conditioned from birth to prioritize instant gratification above all else. These citizens are revealed as mere pieces in a grand design, confined within an ideology dictated by the World Controller. When analyzed through Marxist theory, the author's underlying concerns about these developing systems become apparent. Common Marxist concepts such as homogeneity and reification strengthen the argument that Huxley's work serves as commentary on the flaws in his era's emerging economic system.

Capitalism receives satirical treatment through the Marxist concept of false consciousness. The general population remains ignorant of true class relationships in economic terms, focused solely on personal gain. This results from ideological control of the working class, clearly demonstrated through the conditioning methods in Brave New World. The lower castes - Delta, Gamma, and others - lack genuine free will; hypnopaedia reinforces their compulsion to consume, spend, and indulge. This manipulation stems directly from the World Controller's influence. Hegemony - the complete dominance of social classes by a select group - is evidently at work. Lower classes remain oblivious to their manipulation, literally buying into an ideology that perpetuates the system. The upper classes possess awareness of this reality but remain largely passive; few Alphas or Betas, apart from characters like Bernard, challenge their assigned roles. Indeed, class interactions serve as powerful indicators of capitalism's perceived oppression.

Genuine interpersonal relationships are notably absent in Brave New World. Characters lack individual depth, perhaps suggesting Huxley's view that the convergence of technology and capitalism strips humanity of autonomy and self-expression. Love is nonexistent, and emotional extremes are suppressed; interactions remain superficial, illustrated by men's focus on women's physical attributes (their "pneumatic" qualities) and women's casual attitude toward intimate encounters. Moreover, each social class's acceptance of their hierarchical position reflects capitalism's socioeconomic impact. Their unwavering adherence to communal roles mirrors Marxist observations about the proletariat, who are falsely convinced of their superiority as long as they continue consuming, obeying, and conforming to peer expectations.

Almost four years ago, I enrolled in an Islamic studies course at CBC. One of the main topics of heated debate in the class was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I believe this question is more relevant today than ever before. Looking back at events since 9/11, I have personally witnessed mass media shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to an extreme form of tolerance toward Islam in America. I don't think we could have had a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, with his obvious Muslim family background, back in 2001.

The Prophet's biography intrigues me because, based on my understanding of Muhammad's history, it contradicts what I know of his personality. From my previous knowledge, I believed Muhammad forced people to convert to Islam. He would conquer and take over tribes, then compel them to adopt the Islamic faith. However, according to the biography, Muhammad is portrayed as a kind of martyr who was misunderstood and even showed humility before others. Subsequently, people came to him one by one, recognizing the 'truth' in his teachings and seeking him out.

The uncanny similarities between Jesus's ministry and Muhammad's 'miracles' are particularly striking, especially the account of him multiplying mutton and milk to feed forty men abundantly. This writing style leads me to believe the authors wanted to present Muhammad as a humble prophet who didn't need to prove anything but simply lived in truth and miracles. This approach seems problematic as it diminishes the miracles and life of Jesus Christ, appearing to appropriate Jesus's life and character through Muhammad.

The biography contains numerous stories that seem intended to provide 'witness' accounts or examples of people converting to Islam 'of their own accord.' However, many of these accounts are told from a third-party perspective, with stories passed down through multiple intermediaries. I found this problematic because, while intended to validate the stories' truthfulness, it actually made them less credible and more suspicious.

What troubles me most about this work is its attempt to elevate Muhammad as a godly, humble, endearing, wise, and gentle man. Historical accounts contradict this portrayal of Muhammad as gentle and humble, and I can't help but wonder if modern Muslims are aware of the true historical circumstances of Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and his convictions during his lifetime were quickly abandoned in the evolution of Christian thought after his death. Looking at this history in broad strokes, we observe Christianity's tendency to drift increasingly away from its origins. Today's world appears to demonstrate an ever-growing consciousness and unprecedented progressive inclination. While traditionalists remain and will resist any thinking beyond their taught beliefs, this segment of the population may not be influential enough to shape the whole. Among Christians, historical awareness will grow tremendously in the years to come. A desire will emerge to separate the doctrines added to Christianity over time from the original intentions of the religion's founder. Though it may take decades or centuries, the outcome is inevitable: A great reversal in Christian history's trajectory will occur. There will be a return to its original form. A movement will grow that strips away layers of doctrine, one after another, as if time were moving backward, until only Jesus's original divine message to humanity remains, before other thinkers made their interpretations. When this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, inspiring masses to worship as in Jesus's time, following only his teachings, the church as an institution will remain strong as a guide. However, as the theological clock reverses, Christianity's extreme diversity will consolidate into greater uniformity of belief and practice. Instead of differences between regions, denominations, and divisions, we will see increasing similarities. Human history is full of such great reversals. Consider how Christians, once persecuted and killed by the Roman Empire, later saw that empire become a Christian institution. Our nation has progressed from enslaving African-Americans to seeing African-American leadership. The coming great reversion will unfold within Christianity, undoing history in search of its source, while reducing diversity in the process. Crucially, this process will be facilitated by interpreting Jesus's words metaphorically rather than literally. Looking back far enough, we find only Judaism as Christianity's theological foundation. Monotheism, the concept of divine revelation, and the authority of Hebrew scriptures were central to the religion when Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 BCE. The Jewish population was not unified, being divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

I believe "The Jungle" demonstrates how humans are inherently greedy and self-centered at their core. They only want to take care of themselves and make their lives as comfortable as possible, while never considering those beneath them. "The Jungle" illustrates this in numerous ways, most notably through the factory owners and managers.

These powerful figures are solely focused on expanding their companies and factories to their maximum potential, showing complete disregard for anyone or anything that stands in their way or suffers due to their progress. As Upton Sinclair depicts, the industrial landscape dominates the sky with its imposing buildings and chimneys, spewing endless streams of smoke into the atmosphere - a powerful image of environmental devastation and corporate indifference.

The owners and managers show equal disregard for the workers who generate their wealth. The entire establishment operates as a cauldron of rivalry and hatred, where human value is measured solely in dollars. Workers face grueling hours and could be dismissed without notice or compensation, with no assistance in finding new employment. During this period, the absence of worker protection laws allowed management to exploit their employees freely, forcing them to work at increasing speeds in dangerous conditions.

The residents of Packingtown were expected to endure these horrific conditions both at work and in their living environments, with no support systems or advocacy organizations to assist them. While labor unions existed, they often exploited rather than helped the workers. The working class, predominantly composed of poor immigrants, lived perpetually on the brink of starvation, their fate controlled by men as ruthless as slave drivers. Under such circumstances, the moral degradation of society became inevitable, mirroring the conditions of chattel slavery.

Dream-land is considered one of Edgar Allan Poe's self-proclaimed superior poems. In "Dream-Land," Poe uses the term "Thule" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used the term to refer to an island north of Britain that the Greeks considered the edge of the known world. While Virgil certainly used this term, there is a more contemporary source that deserves recognition. Poe had a strong interest in German authors.

This observation is significant as it demonstrates Poe's acquaintance with Goethe's works. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," notes the similarities between their poems, suggesting that Poe was emulating Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature describes Goethe as a renowned author of the poetic drama "Faust," published in two parts - the first in 1808 and the second in the year of Goethe's death, 1832. Within the second part of Faust lies a short poem titled "The King of Thule." The poem tells of a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet. Following her death, he drinks heavily, mourning his dead queen. Eventually, deciding his time has come, he bequeaths all his possessions to his children except for the goblet. He then walks to a cliff, casts the goblet into the ocean, closes his eyes, and dies. The King of Thule's disposition and the king's portrayal in Dream-Land bear striking similarities, perhaps representing a dark mirror of Poe's own loss and reliance on alcohol.

Both poems can be read as companion pieces, with "Dream-Land" offering descriptions of a dark, lonely Thule haunted by deceased friends and shrouded in colorless shadows - themes that parallel Goethe's grieving king who has lost both his wife and will to live. The entire poem seems to step into the world of Goethe's creation.

Goethe was an influential author whom Poe would have known, if for no other reason than through his admiration of Tennyson. Beyond this connection, Poe would have encountered Goethe's work through the numerous adaptations that followed the original publication.

Under California law, could a customer who was injured after falling on spilled applesauce in a grocery store be awarded punitive damages by proving the store manager acted maliciously, having been informed twice about the spill but failing to have it cleaned for thirty minutes because he was eating dinner?

A judge is unlikely to summarily dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To establish a claim for punitive damages, a plaintiff must demonstrate that the defendant's actions were committed with willful and conscious disregard for the likely resulting harm, while also showing the conduct was despicable. Palmer can argue that Martin should have anticipated the probable harm of leaving a spill uncleaned, especially given that multiple D&D customers had been injured from slipping in the months before Palmer's accident; despite this knowledge, he still failed to address the spill. While Palmer's argument that Martin's actions were despicable may be less compelling, it remains reasonable considering that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in 2009, yet Martin still failed to take appropriate safety measures in his store.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 PM, D&D Markets employee Rich Wayne informed his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin, who was on his dinner break, told Wayne he "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 PM, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Martin about the spill, receiving the same response. At 5:30 PM, plaintiff Jennifer Palmer slipped on the spill and suffered a serious back injury. Before Palmer's accident, five different slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D during 2009. Palmer is now pursuing both compensatory and punitive damages for her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damages claim.

In California, a plaintiff may recover punitive damages for a non-contractual obligation breach if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud or malice." The statute defines malice as either intentional conduct meant to cause harm or, lacking intent, "despicable" conduct committed with "willful and conscious disregard of others' rights or safety." Courts have interpreted conduct as malicious when performed with conscious disregard of plaintiff's rights, specifically when the defendant "was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of their conduct, and willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences."

She had always felt a void within herself - an unfulfillable yearning. It began around age 14, just as she entered her teenage years, and persisted until she was 17. Eventually, she realized she longed for someone rather than something. Yet no boys caught her interest, despite several awkward attempts from those who were drawn to her. This peculiarity often led her to question herself, wondering what could cause such unusual feelings in a teenage girl. Years of reflection had produced theories, but none satisfactory enough to seriously consider. So she continued living, perpetually puzzled by her desires.

Home life was typically serene. Her parents were gentle, peaceful people who rarely argued, either with each other or with their daughter. The only occasional conflicts arose from her assertions of independence and free spirit. Though born to tranquil parents, she balanced their calm nature with her vibrant, engaging personality, making her widely liked for both her energy and kindness.

This day, however, broke from the usual peace. While wandering between rooms seeking inspiration, she heard her mother's beautiful voice release a sharp scream from the kitchen. She rushed in, panic-stricken, calling out "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" There lay her mother on the floor, breathing heavily through pain, repeatedly whimpering "Ow." She knelt beside her mother, reaching out to help. Between labored breaths, her mother managed, "Ouch... sweet-heart, I... need you to take me to... the hospital." Grateful for her strength training, the daughter carefully followed her mother's instructions to lift her. She carried her to the car, gently laid her across the back seat, and drove.

The hospital visit brought its typical mix of antiseptic smells and anxiety, though she barely noticed, focused entirely on her mother's needs. She rushed in carrying her mother, calling urgently for medical help. Concerned staff quickly surrounded them, transferring her mother onto a gurney. As they whisked her mother away for examination, she was left alone with her worry.

The cause? Her mother had fallen from a stepstool while reaching for a vase in the highest cabinet.

This study aimed to demonstrate that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternative Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," correlates with lower risks of chronic heart disease (CHD), stroke, and stroke-related mortality. The aMed diet represents a modified version of the Mediterranean diet, characterized by increased consumption of plant-based foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (in comparison to saturated fats) and fish, while reducing intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Previous prospective studies have documented an inverse relationship between Mediterranean diet adherence and overall cardiovascular (CVD) mortality. An intervention trial demonstrated that the Mediterranean diet was more effective than low-fat diets in achieving weight loss and improving the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. Earlier studies had not specifically addressed stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological investigation followed 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, without prior CVD or diabetes history, who participated in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study involving 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Between 1984 and 2004, researchers calculated aMed diet scores six times using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to evaluate nutrient intake over the previous year. Over 95% of nurses maintained participation throughout the 20-year study period. FFQs underwent validation studies, and reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were verified through medical records, hospital documentation, autopsies, or death certificates. When records were unavailable, cases were designated as "probable" and included, comprising approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions.

To minimize random individual variation and better represent long-term dietary patterns, cumulative averages of the aMed scores from repeated FFQs were calculated by averaging scores from two previous years. The study accounted for potential confounding factors by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Using Cox proportional-hazard modeling, researchers evaluated the relationship between aMed scores and CHD and stroke risk, employing separate models for fatal and nonfatal events of each type.

Higher adherence to the Mediterranean diet, indicated by elevated aMed diet scores, was associated with reduced risk of both CHD and stroke in women. During the 20-year follow-up period, researchers documented 2,391 incident cases of CHD, 1,763 incident cases of stroke, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths (combined fatal CHD and strokes). Women in the highest aMed quintile showed lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

According to the sign, Hitler is alive in Burma.

Ellen Page, the star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner, holding a piece of cardboard above her head with this disturbing message written in Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian country governed by a tyrannical military junta that seized power through a coup in 1962. In 2007, several street protests emerged - the first public demonstrations in a decade. These protests, led by numerous Burmese monks, became known as the "Saffron Revolution," named after the color of the monks' robes. After the initial uprising, the general public began taking interest in the protests. While the Burmese government initially reluctantly tolerated the monks' peaceful gatherings, the situation soon escalated into what some described as an outright war between the monks and the military junta, with forces actively raiding and plundering monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were immediately arrested upon discovery, with Japanese photojournalist Kenji Nagai being killed on September 27, 2007, merely for attending a street protest. While the official death toll stands at 13, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army days before the official report, stated, "The number of people killed in recent days far exceeds what you've heard. The death toll runs into several thousand."

This pattern is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities in our world, governments' desire to suppress dissent and maintain absolute control over their citizens has existed as long as civilization itself. Ancient Roman emperors claimed divine selection to exercise complete control over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are considered actual deities, sent to guide their people to prosperity through the creation of Motorola phones and hara-kiri, while our current president, George W. Bush, holds weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary of the Republican Party.

Among the most notorious examples are the June 4th, 1989 protest in Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to protest against authoritarian rule. The death toll from this event varies widely, with official Chinese government figures citing 200-300 deaths, while Chinese Red Cross reports indicate between 2,000-3,000 casualties. Another example is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, supported by the Rwandan government, began systematically killing all Tutsis and political moderates, regardless of their ethnic background. Hitler's 'Third Reich', a period spanning several years and countries during which anyone of Jewish descent was rounded up and killed, represents another extreme example.

Duke Ellington's jazz legacy stems largely from his longevity and, consequently, his creative ability to shape his orchestra. While Ellington's piano presence remains subtle in many of the compositions chosen for this assignment, his brilliance as a composer shone through in creating rich and intricate pieces that highlighted the individual talents of his band members. Ellington masterfully crafted frameworks that allowed soloists to improvise freely, while also writing tightly orchestrated passages that leveraged the distinctive styles of band members to emphasize musical ideas. In doing so, he enhanced the overall orchestral tone, creating unique and cohesive sounds tailored to each piece. His deep understanding of individual players' sounds and their collective harmony within an expanding ensemble enabled him to compose some of jazz history's most groundbreaking and brilliant works.

According to the Grove Music dictionary's discussion of Ellington's sound and innovation, Creole Love Call is noted for its pioneering use of voice "as a jazz instrument" - an approach he maintained throughout his career. This early work exemplifies Ellington's technique of using vocals to add texture and color without being constrained by lyrics. Creole Love Call also showcases his talent for complementing his soloists' styles, a characteristic evident throughout his musical journey. This measured, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece unfolds across six choruses:

Chorus 1: A vocal-reed dialogue, beginning with smooth, melodic vocals that transition to a rougher texture.
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo expanding on the core melody, emphasizing extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: An soaring clarinet solo in the upper register, supported by subtle syncopated piano.
Chorus 4: The full ensemble echoes the opening chorus through brass and reed section interplay.
Chorus 5: The piece reaches its peak as reeds initiate call and response in high register, backed by syncopated stop-time from brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: Returning to the initial structure, featuring vocal-reed dialogue with the voice adopting an instrumental "growl" technique.
Tag: Concluding with a vocal run and distinctive dissonant trombone ending.

This vocal approach to tonal coloring became a hallmark of Ellington's style. In Hot and Bothered, recorded the following year, Ellington merged precise orchestration with his keen sense for tonal color. The interplay between "Bubber" Miley's muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing creates a rich harmony by combining Miley's vocal-like playing with Cox's instrumental-style vocals. These concepts further evolved in It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing), where Ellington skillfully features Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, a longtime orchestra member, introducing the melody on muted trombone.

Why do organisms develop in the way they do? Are there limitations or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change? Although D'Arcy Thompson noted in 1917 that "zoologists have barely begun to define even the simplest organic forms in mathematical language," this statement remains true today. In recent times, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeleton formation through both ontogeny and phylogeny.

A shell can be understood as a tube-like structure that travels through 360 degrees of space over time. These spiral revolutions, known as whorls, coil around an imaginary central axis called the columella. The rate at which the whorls expand can vary, and they are separated by a continuous line called the suture. In most shells, the final whorl (body whorl) is the largest, while the spire comprises all preceding whorls. The shell terminates in an apex at one end and a base at the other, with an aperture through which the animal extends.

Shells can be examined from various perspectives: apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. The standard orientation presents the shell in an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upward.

The shell's growth can be understood as a series of apertures progressing through time and space as the animal constructs its shell. This growth pattern can be traced mathematically using coordinates of each whorl's aperture center and its dimensions, allowing for mathematical modeling and potential modifications of mollusk shell development.

The infant and child mortality rate in Indonesia has remained relatively constant over the past decade. While the country is progressing toward achieving many of the Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation targets, the improvement rates for child and maternal health fall far short of the necessary advances needed to reach their targets by 2015. The various reasons for these deficiencies will be discussed below, suggesting the need to strengthen the healthcare system rather than focusing on programmatic interventions.

Indonesia has made progress in increasing the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% of births now meeting this standard. However, this category still includes traditional practitioners, such as midwives, who cannot provide medical interventions in cases of complicated pregnancies (explaining the high percentage of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage). In essence, the improvements shown in this particular indicator are somewhat deceptive, and considerable work remains to be done. Furthermore, there has been a decrease in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five being treated by healthcare professionals. While postnatal care data is incomplete, it's evident that this area is also problematic, with low rates throughout the country.

Cesarean section rates remain lower than expected, at approximately 4%. These rates also highlight another concerning disparity: while urban areas have a 7% c-section rate, rural areas show only 2%. This underscores the issue of inequitable healthcare coverage across the country. Healthcare services are clearly concentrated in urban areas. Another access issue involves vertical equity, with a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and wealthiest quintiles. The poor evidently face greater difficulties accessing healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket expenses.

In considering next steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the fundamental question is how to most effectively address the service gap. Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing exclusively on pre- and post-pregnancy care? While programmatic approaches to address the aforementioned problems are appealing, as "vertical approaches" targeting specific improvement sectors have more focused, manageable objectives and typically yield faster results, there are important drawbacks to consider. A major concern is that heavy investment in programming for one particular health sector often depletes funding for other areas and attracts human resources to the better-funded sector (as exemplified by international HIV/AIDS funding's impact on family planning). Additionally, running multiple parallel programs leads to service duplication and lack of coordination, resulting in increased paperwork and administrative burden for supplies and funding.

The categorization of popular music has expanded so dramatically over the last 100 years that it now encompasses so many genres that it's challenging to definitively list them all. Adding to this complexity, most if not all genres - rap, rock, country, jazz, folk, to name just a few - have given rise to multiple sub-genres and sub-sub-genres within their domain. One could argue that the sub-genre of Heavy Metal has evolved into one of the most diverse and expressive genres in all of popular music over the past 40 years. It's expressive because it showcases a wide range of emotions, though they tend to gravitate toward the darker end of the spectrum. Its diversity is evident in how, shortly after the genre's inception, people recognized its inherent flexibility and began utilizing it to create their own sub-genres, which then spawned sub-sub-genres - a chain that continues to this day.

Several decades before the Surrealist artists began creating their dream-like works, the artist Henri Rousseau was crafting his own dreams, both literally and metaphorically. "The Dream," a 1910 painting by the renowned Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman overwhelmed by the wonders of the land she visits in a dream but also Rousseau's own personal dreams and aspirations as a painter. From the beginning of his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise from other artists and art lovers, finding himself faced with a difficult internal dilemma in pursuing this goal. "The Dream" is Henri Rousseau's work that best reflects his lifelong internal struggle: whether to conform to or imitate certain painting styles to gain acceptance from the critical art world he so admired, or to allow himself to develop creatively independent and unique, forging his own path as he went along.

Many great thinkers have proposed an intimate relationship between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there is a fundamental reason for this connection. As John Keats expresses in "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - that is all you know on earth, and all you need to know." Much of our life's knowledge comes through education or experience. Yet, as Keats suggests, our appreciation of ethics and aesthetics seems to develop without these conventional teaching methods.

Both ethics and aesthetics aim to describe rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are largely attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature moves us, or why an action is moral, rather than establishing rigid rules for judging or creating good art or ethical behavior.

More significantly, neither artistic nor moral criticism can fully capture the essence of goodness or beauty. While we might discuss the Mona Lisa in terms of composition, contrast, or cultural context, these elements alone cannot explain what makes it masterful. People often preface their analysis of beloved art or literature with "There's just something about it" before delving into more detailed explanations. I believe both artistic and moral qualities resist complete reduction to their component parts. As Flannery O'Connor notes, "A story communicates something that cannot be expressed any other way... you tell a story because a mere statement would fall short." Something transcendent remains beyond even the most thorough analysis of literature, and I believe ethics shares this quality. As Wittgenstein observes, "Ethics cannot be expressed. Ethics is transcendental." This ineffable quality, this je ne sais quoi, represents the most powerful aspect of both art and morality, creating a bridge between them.

The connection between morality and art runs deep because we experience both most profoundly at a noumenal level, to use Kant's terminology. They touch us in ways we can feel but never fully explain. This connection strengthens further in literature. As McKean observes, literature's distinctive feature, its truly unique aspect, lies in its moral dimension. While moral standards might not apply to all arts, such as music, they seem as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living inherently involves values, and literature's significance stems precisely from the values we discover within it.

Today's Germany is regarded as a powerful force, a unified nation with its own unique cultural blend stretching from the shadow of the Alps in Munich to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This same culture can be felt from Cologne on the Rhine, through Germany's heartland, to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. Given such a distinctive culture, it's not surprising that the Germany we know today emerged from various sources and tribes.

Germania is the ancestral homeland of the German people. The origin of its name is heavily debated among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed the name came from a Germanic tribe then known as the Tungri, who had previously been called Germans before crossing the Rhine and engaging in battle with Gallic forces. Julius Caesar first used the word "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he subdued the Gauls and fought against Germanic tribes who frequently crossed the Rhine under dubious pretexts. He adopted this word from the Gauls themselves, using it to distinguish between those he had conquered (the Gauls) and those he had not. While the origin remains uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gallic language. Others claim the meaning derives from the spear they used in warfare, known as a "ger," or perhaps from the Old Irish word "garim" meaning "to shout," suggesting that the Germans were loud or noisy.

The play Twelfth Night appears to suggest that while disguise can serve as a useful tool for extended deception, one must ultimately shed this artificial persona or risk losing their true self in the process. A significant challenge in ending any deception lies in the potential alienation that follows. Thus, one must ultimately choose between preserving their authentic self or maintaining their relationships with others. While some might react indifferently to discovering they've been deceived, others may take profound offense at the masquerade.

The matter of gender-based deception proves particularly complex, raising numerous secondary concerns - chief among them being the motivation. What drives an individual to abandon their true identity and assume the disguise of another gender? In Viola's case, it clearly stems from self-preservation: "I'll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count..."

Finding herself in unfamiliar territory, Viola deems it necessary to adopt a male persona for protection. While this strategy proves effective, it also isolates her from potential female allies, depriving her of crucial support networks. The situation grows more complicated when her masculine portrayal proves so convincing that Olivia mistakes her for Sebastian and falls in love with her. "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay." Further complications arise from the suppressed romantic tension between her and Orsino: "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me."

While perhaps progressive for its time, modern readers might interpret Twelfth Night as an exploration of how deception can catalyze the emergence of repressed emotions, particularly in Olivia and Orsino's cases. Certain passages suggest these characters harbor unexpressed subconscious desires that Viola/Cesario's presence forces them to confront. However, Olivia's swift transfer of affections from Cesario to Sebastian, and her eventual acceptance of Viola as family rather than a romantic interest ("A sister, you are she") suggests Shakespeare may be satirizing the superficial nature of attraction in his society rather than exploring deeper questions of gender and sexuality.

German colonial rule has been recognized by various observers for its brutality, particularly regarding the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama people in German South West Africa. Naturally, such a vast colonial empire cannot be characterized by such a simple description. The German colonial empire exhibited as much diversity in its policies and governing style as it did in its geography. Educational provisions across the colonies showed similar variation. When the British assumed control of German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they discovered a substantial population of educated and literate Africans. German educational initiatives in Cameroon and other colonies also received praise from contemporary writers.

The situation in South West Africa (modern-day Namibia) stood in marked contrast. Unlike East Africa, where the government established state schools and took an active role in native education, in South West Africa the education of indigenous peoples was delegated almost entirely to missionary societies with minimal government support. The government did, however, invest considerable resources in European education in the colony, establishing state schools and providing stronger support and oversight for missionary schools serving European settlers. These educational policies had lasting implications for South West Africa, even after German rule ended. While other German colonies could boast significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to South West Africa's divergent experience. This study aims to broaden the discussion by identifying these factors, with particular emphasis on new research regarding settler and colonial authority attitudes toward native Africans.

There exists extensive literature on education in the German colonial empire. Most sources are in German and date from the early twentieth century, during or shortly after German colonial rule. Early works primarily focused on describing colonial educational systems. Later English-language scholarship expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education across German colonies and more detailed analysis of specific educational aspects. These studies revealed significant variations in educational systems between colonies. Cohen's study of education in South West Africa and East Africa stands as the most notable work directly addressing this paper's topic. Cohen's comparative analysis of the two colonies' educational systems explores factors accounting for their differences, attributing many of South West Africa's distinctive educational characteristics to its large settler population.

Compared to Germany's other colonial territories, South West Africa enjoyed a relatively temperate climate, despite much of its territory being arid desert. The European population in South West Africa reflected these more hospitable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites resided in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in East Africa, the colony with the next largest settler population.

The United States and Mexico exemplify two nations that were once caught in a persistent rivalry lasting 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The rivalry peaked during the Mexican-American War (1846-1848), when the United States defeated Mexico and acquired Texas and the American Southwest. Multiple confrontations occurred between both nations, finally subsiding just before World War I. The conflict originated from fundamental differences in religion, culture, and traditions, as well as competing material interests.

This pattern mirrors many other nations experiencing enduring rivalries with their neighbors. Countries sharing borders frequently encounter conflicting interests that foster rivalrous relationships. The U.S.-Mexico case reflects a common pattern among neighboring nations with sustained rivalries. David M. Pletcher (1977) notes that among Latin American nations, only Mexico and Cuba presented persistent diplomatic challenges for the United States, while other Latin American countries maintained generally positive relations.

Religious differences created a significant divide between the two nations, a common historical phenomenon. As Sally Frahm (2001) observes, American opposition to Catholicism and monarchy in the 18th and 19th centuries paralleled their later resistance to fascism and communism in the 20th century. Similar to how the Cold War combined ideological differences with competition over vital interests, the U.S.-Mexico rivalry centered on religious rather than political ideologies. This antagonism stemmed from historical English-Spanish tensions, with both nations inheriting their former colonial powers' mutual suspicion.

During the 57-year rivalry period, Diehl and Goerts (2000) document 17 distinct disputes between Mexico and the United States. Most conflicts involved territorial issues, particularly border raids and frontier challenges. Both nations eventually deployed military forces to address the persistent problem of cross-border banditry and outlaw activities.

The rivalry gradually diminished as Mexico became increasingly economically dependent on the United States, and American priorities shifted from territorial expansion to economic engagement with Mexico in the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply rooted need for security and stability that I lacked as a child. "You'll always find work; people will always get sick" was the mantra I heard repeatedly as I grew through adolescence and beyond. So - although my dream was to be a scientist or journalist - preferably both - I chose nursing.

Nevertheless, there I was: 46 years old and single, with barely any savings and unable to work. To this day I remain disabled, and after 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I literally have nothing left to call my own. I get by, but each day is a struggle that challenges my security, safety, and self-worth. While nothing in my life is certain anymore, one truth remains clear: I couldn't have survived these years without the support of my family and a few good friends, regardless of how strong I was. And trust me, when real disaster strikes, you don't feel strong at all.

My point is that life will always bring emergencies - both large and small. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well-prepared you are, some challenges are simply too big to face alone.

I completely agree that we in the U.S. need to stop placing all our trust in big government's "basket" - heaven knows it's deteriorating anyway. However, I'd much rather see Americans learning to trust each other again - learning to help one another and to ask for help - rather than each of us retreating to our backyards to build individual fallout shelters.

American Conservatives speak of the "rugged individualism" that built this nation, but in reality, what sustained our ancestors through hard times wasn't individualism - it was compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't reach the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit: first aid supplies, water purification tablets, and plastic sheeting with duct tape for windows in case of a biological attack. I have multiple flashlights and various batteries, plenty of candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods too. If you have the land and resources for a small farm and can preserve your own food - do it. It's an excellent idea, as is having a wood stove, provided you don't live in an apartment.

But while you're doing all this, make sure to get to know your neighbors.

Around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born who would later be known as Buddha. Throughout his life, he renounced worldly matters and achieved enlightenment, and his teachings gave rise to Buddhism—with its most orthodox branch known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion, now approximately twenty-five centuries old, appears quite different today compared to Buddha's time. This transformation is evident everywhere, for example in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where an annual water-cutting ceremony takes place. Both monks and laypeople participate in this ceremony, which holds religious significance, despite Buddha never having taught about such festivities. These differences span from superficial traditions to the soteriological essence of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, from both monastic and lay perspectives, has had to adapt its doctrinal principles over time. This adaptation can be attributed to forces both external and internal, hostile and benign.

A number of key terms will be frequently used in this discussion. There is the concept of internal versus external forces. An internal force is defined as one originating from members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of their monastic status. An external force comes from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that harms or intends to harm the Buddhist community—arising from a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force neither intends to help nor harm the Buddhist community—though it may ultimately do either as a consequence. These terms will appear repeatedly throughout this discussion.

First, it is essential to examine the fundamentals of the religion—the core doctrines of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma essentially comprises the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the rules of discipline, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains Buddhism's metaphysical aspects. These metaphysical concepts include Anatta—the absence of self, Dukkha—the inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—the impermanence of all things. Only by understanding these concepts can one end Sansara, the continuous cycle of death and rebirth. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when enlightenment is achieved. The Vinaya Pitaka establishes life's rules. For laypeople, there are five precepts (abstaining from killing, lying, stealing, sexual misconduct, and intoxicating substances). Monks must follow many more disciplinary rules. The most fundamental doctrinal concept in Buddhism is the four noble truths: First, Dukkha—the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.
